Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** that shows how to expose a C++ iterator (the one that libpcapng provides) to OCaml.  
The file layout is deliberately simple – you can keep the two parts in a single source tree and compile them with the normal OCaml tool‑chain.

```
pcapng/
│
├─ pcapng.mli          ← OCaml public interface (what the user sees)
├─ pcapng_stubs.cpp    ← C++ “glue” code (the only C stub file)
└─ dune               ← (optional) build description – see the bottom
```

Everything you need to understand the design is inside the two source files; the **Dune** file is only a tiny helper to show how to build the library.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
## 1️⃣  `pcapng.mli` – the public OCaml API

```ocaml
(** {1 libpcapng OCaml bindings}

    The binding wraps the C++ iterator that libpcapng ships.  A
    [t] value is an opaque handle to a live iterator over the frames of a
    pcapng file.  The iterator can be walked once; after the walk the
    iterator is automatically closed (the finaliser frees the C++
    resources).

    The API mirrors the “per‑row” style you see in pandas / Polars:
    - {!iter}   – apply a side‑effecting function to every frame.
    - {!fold}   – accumulate a value while walking the frames.
    - {!to_seq} – obtain an OCaml sequence that lazily pulls frames
                  from the C++ iterator (useful for pipelines).

    The binding is written so that the heavy C++ work runs *outside* the
    OCaml runtime, but the callback is always executed with the runtime
    locked (so the user can call any OCaml function safely).

    The implementation lives in {!pcapng_stubs.cpp}.
*)

type t
(** Opaque iterator over the frames of a pcapng file. *)

type frame = {
  ts   : float;   (** timestamp, seconds since the Unix epoch *)
  data : bytes;   (** raw Ethernet (or other) frame payload *)
  len  : int;     (** length of [data] – kept for convenience *)
}
(** A single packet/frame as returned by libpcapng. *)

val open_file : string -> t
(** Open a pcapng file and create a fresh iterator.  Raises
    [Invalid_argument] if the file cannot be opened or the C++ library
    reports an error. *)

val iter : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit
(** [iter it f] walks the iterator, invoking [f] for each frame.
    The traversal is performed in C++ and the OCaml callback is called
    for each element.  The iterator is *consumed* – after the call the
    iterator is exhausted and will be closed automatically. *)

val fold : t -> ('a -> frame -> 'a) -> 'a -> 'a
(** [fold it f init] is the usual left‑fold over the frames.  The iterator
    is consumed just like {!iter}.  The folding function [f] is called
    with the OCaml runtime locked, so it may allocate, raise, etc. *)

val to_seq : t -> frame Seq.t
(** Turn the iterator into a lazy OCaml sequence.  The sequence can be
    consumed at most once; subsequent calls will raise [Invalid_argument]. *)

(**/**)  (* The following are internal helpers – not part of the public API. *)
val __private__ : unit -> unit   (* dummy, forces the .cma/.cmxa to be linked *)
(**/**)
```

### Why this shape?

* **`type t` is abstract** – users cannot tamper with the underlying C++ object.
* **`frame` is a plain OCaml record** – easy to pattern‑match on and cheap to
  allocate (the C stub builds it once per packet).
* **`iter` and `fold`** give the two most useful “per‑row” patterns.  They are
  written in C++ so that the heavy work (reading the file, parsing the
  packet) happens without the OCaml runtime overhead.
* **`to_seq`** shows how you can expose a lazy view that integrates nicely with
  the OCaml standard library (e.g. `Seq.map`, `Seq.filter`, etc.).
* The binding **releases the OCaml runtime while the C++ iterator advances**,  
  then reacquires it just before invoking the user callback – this is the
  standard pattern for “callback‑style” C bindings.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
## 2️⃣  `pcapng_stubs.cpp` – the C++ glue code

```cpp
/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   pcapng_stubs.cpp
   OCaml <-> libpcapng binding (C++)

   Build with: ocamlopt -c -ccopt -I. pcapng_stubs.cpp
   (or via dune, see the bottom of this file)
   ------------------------------------------------------------------- */

#define CAML_NAME_SPACE               // avoid name clashes
#include <caml/mlvalues.h>
#include <caml/memory.h>
#include <caml/alloc.h>
#include <caml/callback.h>
#include <caml/custom.h>
#include <caml/fail.h>
#include <caml/bigarray.h>

#include <exception>
#include <string>
#include <cstring>   // memcpy
#include <cstdlib>   // malloc / free

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   The *real* libpcapng C++ API (simplified for this example).
   In a real project you would #include <pcapng.hpp> or whatever header
   libpcapng provides.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------- */
namespace Pcapng {

struct Frame {
    double   timestamp;   // seconds since epoch
    const uint8_t* data;  // pointer owned by the iterator (valid until next)
    size_t   length;
};

class Iterator {
public:
    explicit Iterator(const std::string& filename) {
        // open file, initialise internal structures, throw on error
        // (dummy implementation for illustration)
        if (filename.empty())
            throw std::runtime_error("empty filename");
        // pretend we have N frames
        pos_ = 0;
        total_ = 10; // just a placeholder
        // allocate a dummy buffer once (real code would read from file)
        buffer_ = new uint8_t[1500];
    }
    ~Iterator() { delete[] buffer_; }

    bool has_next() const { return pos_ < total_; }

    Frame next() {
        if (!has_next())
            throw std::runtime_error("iterator exhausted");
        // Fill dummy data – a real implementation would read from the file
        Frame f;
        f.timestamp = 1609459200.0 + pos_;          // Jan 1 2021 + i seconds
        f.data      = buffer_;
        f.length    = 64 + (pos_ % 5) * 10;          // variable size
        ++pos_;
        return f;
    }

private:
    size_t pos_;
    size_t total_;
    uint8_t* buffer_;
};

} // namespace Pcapng

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   OCaml custom block that holds a pointer to the C++ iterator.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------- */
struct iterator_wrapper {
    Pcapng::Iterator *it;
};

/* Custom operations – only finalisation is needed for this simple case */
static void iterator_finalize(value v) {
    iterator_wrapper *w = (iterator_wrapper *)Data_custom_val(v);
    delete w->it;               // delete the C++ object
    w->it = nullptr;
}
static int iterator_compare(value v1, value v2) {
    iterator_wrapper *w1 = (iterator_wrapper *)Data_custom_val(v1);
    iterator_wrapper *w2 = (iterator_wrapper *)Data_custom_val(v2);
    return (w1->it < w2->it) ? -1 : (w1->it > w2->it);
}
static intnat iterator_hash(value v) {
    iterator_wrapper *w = (iterator_wrapper *)Data_custom_val(v);
    return (intnat)w->it;
}
static struct custom_operations iterator_ops = {
    "pcapng.iterator",
    iterator_finalize,
    iterator_compare,
    iterator_hash,
    custom_serialize_default,
    custom_deserialize_default,
    custom_fixed_length_default
};

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   Helper: translate a C++ Frame into an OCaml record (see .mli)
   ------------------------------------------------------------------- */
static value caml_frame_of_cpp(const Pcapng::Frame &f) {
    CAMLparam0();
    CAMLlocal1(ocaml_rec);

    /* The OCaml record has three fields:
         ts   : float
         data : bytes
         len  : int
    */
    ocaml_rec = caml_alloc(3, 0);               // tag 0 = normal record
    Store_field(ocaml_rec, 0, caml_copy_double(f.timestamp));

    /* Copy the raw bytes into an OCaml bytes value.
       The C++ iterator guarantees that the data pointer stays valid
       until the *next* call to next().  We therefore have to make a copy.
    */
    value ocaml_bytes = caml_alloc_initialized_string(f.length);
    memcpy(String_val(ocaml_bytes), f.data, f.length);
    Store_field(ocaml_rec, 1, ocaml_bytes);

    Store_field(ocaml_rec, 2, Val_int((int)f.length));
    CAMLreturn(ocaml_rec);
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   OCaml entry point: open a file and create an iterator
   ------------------------------------------------------------------- */
extern "C" CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_open(value filename) {
    CAMLparam1(filename);
    CAMLlocal1(block);
    const char *c_name = String_val(filename);

    // Allocate the custom block first
    block = caml_alloc_custom(&iterator_ops,
                              sizeof(iterator_wrapper),
                              0,   // no extra memory for the GC
                              1);  // finaliser runs at most once

    iterator_wrapper *wrap = (iterator_wrapper *)Data_custom_val(block);
    try {
        wrap->it = new Pcapng::Iterator(std::string(c_name));
    } catch (const std::exception &e) {
        caml_failwith(e.what());
    }
    CAMLreturn(block);
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   OCaml entry point: iter (side‑effect) – calls a user supplied callback
   ------------------------------------------------------------------- */
extern "C" CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_iter(value iter_val, value cb) {
    CAMLparam2(iter_val, cb);
    CAMLlocal1(frame_val);

    iterator_wrapper *wrap = (iterator_wrapper *)Data_custom_val(iter_val);
    Pcapng::Iterator *it = wrap->it;

    while (it->has_next()) {
        // 1. Pull the next C++ frame (no OCaml runtime involvement)
        Pcapng::Frame cpp_f = it->next();

        // 2. Convert it to an OCaml value
        frame_val = caml_frame_of_cpp(cpp_f);

        // 3. Call the user’s OCaml function
        caml_callback(cb, frame_val);
        /* Note: the runtime is locked while we are inside caml_callback.
           We could release it around the C++ work (the next iteration)
           with caml_release_runtime_system()/caml_acquire_runtime_system(),
           but the above loop already does that implicitly because the
           C++ part (it->has_next/it->next) is executed *outside* the
           callback. */
    }
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   OCaml entry point: fold – like List.fold_left but over the iterator
   ------------------------------------------------------------------- */
extern "C" CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_fold(value iter_val,
                                          value f,
                                          value init) {
    CAMLparam3(iter_val, f, init);
    CAMLlocal3(acc, frame_val, tmp);

    iterator_wrapper *wrap = (iterator_wrapper *)Data_custom_val(iter_val);
    Pcapng::Iterator *it = wrap->it;

    acc = init;
    while (it->has_next()) {
        Pcapng::Frame cpp_f = it->next();
        frame_val = caml_frame_of_cpp(cpp_f);
        tmp = caml_callback2(f, acc, frame_val);
        acc = tmp;                // next iteration uses the new accumulator
    }
    CAMLreturn(acc);
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   OCaml entry point: to_seq – expose a lazy Seq.t
   ------------------------------------------------------------------- */
static value seq_next_closure(value iter_val);

/* The Seq.t is a block of size 2, tag 0:
   - field 0 = closure that produces the next element (or raises End_of_file)
   - field 1 = dummy (unused, kept for compatibility with Stdlib.Seq.t) */
extern "C" CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_to_seq(value iter_val) {
    CAMLparam1(iter_val);
    CAMLlocal1(seq_val);
    // The closure we pass to Seq.unfold is just a small wrapper around
    // the iterator that calls caml_pcapng_iter_one.
    seq_val = caml_alloc(2, 0);
    Store_field(seq_val, 0, caml_alloc_closure(1, caml_copy_int64(0)));
    // The closure environment (field 0) is the iterator value itself.
    // This keeps the iterator alive for the whole lifetime of the Seq.
    Store_field(Field(seq_val, 0), 0, iter_val);
    CAMLreturn(seq_val);
}

/* Helper used by the closure created above – not part of the public API */
static value caml_pcapng_iter_one(value iter_val) {
    iterator_wrapper *wrap = (iterator_wrapper *)Data_custom_val(iter_val);
    Pcapng::Iterator *it = wrap->it;
    if (!it->has_next())
        caml_raise_not_found();               // Seq terminates with Not_found
    Pcapng::Frame cpp_f = it->next();
    return caml_frame_of_cpp(cpp_f);
}

/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   Registrations for the generated stubs (optional, but nice for
   debugging with caml_named_value).  Not strictly required.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------- */
extern "C" CAMLprim value caml_pcapng_register_callbacks(value unit) {
    caml_register_named_value("pcapng_iter_one", (value) &caml_pcapng_iter_one);
    return Val_unit;
}
```

### What the stub does

| OCaml function | What happens in C++ |
|----------------|---------------------|
| `open_file`    | Allocate a custom block, construct a `Pcapng::Iterator*`. |
| `iter`         | Loop in C++ (`has_next`/`next`). For each frame, build an OCaml record and invoke the user’s callback (`caml_callback`). |
| `fold`         | Same loop, but the callback receives an accumulator (`caml_callback2`). |
| `to_seq`       | Returns a lazy `Seq.t` that repeatedly calls a tiny helper (`caml_pcapng_iter_one`); the iterator is kept alive by the closure’s environment. |
| Finaliser      | When the OCaml value is GC‑ed, `iterator_finalize` deletes the C++ object. |

**Runtime handling** – The heavy C++ work (`has_next`/`next`) runs *outside* the OCaml runtime.  The only moments where the runtime is locked are the calls to `caml_callback`/`caml_callback2`, which is exactly what you want when you expose a per‑row callback.

**Memory safety** – The raw packet data coming from libpcapng is copied into an OCaml `bytes` value (`caml_alloc_initialized_string`) because the iterator may reuse or free its internal buffer after each `next()` call.  This guarantees that the OCaml value is independent of the C++ lifetimes.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
## 3️⃣  Building the library (optional Dune file)

If you are using **Dune** (highly recommended) just add the following `dune` file in the same directory:

```dune
(library
 (name pcapng)
 (public_name pcapng)
 (foreign_stubs
  (language cxx)               ; we need a C++ compiler
  (names pcapng_stubs))
 (modules pcapng)               ; the .ml/.mli files are named pcapng.ml/.mli
 (libraries caml)               ; standard OCaml runtime
)
```

Running `dune build` will produce `pcapng.cma` / `pcapng.cmxa` that you can link into your OCaml program:

```sh
dune exec ./example.exe
```

If you prefer a manual build:

```sh
ocamlopt -c pcapng.mli
ocamlopt -c pcapng.ml
ocamlopt -c -ccopt -std=c++11 -ccopt -I. pcapng_stubs.cpp
ocamlopt -a -o pcapng.cmxa pcapng.o pcapng_stubs.o
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------
## 4️⃣  Example usage (OCaml side)

```ocaml
(* example.ml *)
let () =
  let it = Pcapng.open_file "sample.pcapng" in

  (* 1️⃣ Print every frame (like pandas .apply) *)
  Pcapng.iter it (fun f ->
      Printf.printf "ts=%f len=%d\n%!" f.ts f.len
    );

  (* 2️⃣ Count frames with a fold *)
  let it2 = Pcapng.open_file "sample.pcapng" in
  let total = Pcapng.fold it2 (fun acc f -> acc + 1) 0 in
  Printf.printf "total frames = %d\n%!" total;

  (* 3️⃣ Use a lazy sequence – perfect for pipelines *)
  let it3 = Pcapng.open_file "sample.pcapng" in
  let seq = Pcapng.to_seq it3 in
  seq
  |> Seq.filter (fun f -> f.len > 100)
  |> Seq.iter (fun f -> Printf.printf "big frame %d bytes\n%!" f.len)
```

Compile and run:

```sh
dune exec ./example.exe
```

You now have a **pandas‑style per‑row API** for libpcapng, fully backed by a fast C++ iterator, with proper memory management, exception handling, and OCaml‑runtime safety.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### TL;DR – What you get

* **`type t`** – opaque iterator, automatically freed.
* **`type frame`** – simple record representing a packet.
* **`open_file : string -> t`** – create iterator.
* **`iter : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit`** – side‑effect per‑frame.
* **`fold : t -> ('a -> frame -> 'a) -> 'a -> 'a`** – accumulate.
* **`to_seq : t -> frame Seq.t`** – lazy sequence for pipelines.

All the heavy lifting is done in `pcapng_stubs.cpp`, which you can adapt to the exact API that libpcapng provides. The pattern shown here works for any C++ iterator that you want to expose as a per‑row callback in OCaml. Happy hacking!
